# Luke Skywalker page on starwars.fandom.com — character evolution across trilogy eras, expanded universe, and canon shifts
{"eventId": "evt_luke_001", "eventType": "sentence_first_seen", "claimId": "clm_luke_001", "fromRevisionId": 1280001001, "toRevisionId": 1280001002, "section": "Biography", "before": "", "after": "Luke Skywalker was the son of Anakin Skywalker, a Jedi Knight who served as a general during the Clone Wars before falling to the dark side and becoming the Sith Lord Darth Vader.", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "The claim establishing Luke's parentage first appeared in this revision.", "detail": "Added after the 1980 release of The Empire Strikes Back, which revealed Vader as Luke's father. This edit replaced the earlier text that described Anakin as 'killed by Darth Vader.'"}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2023-06-15T09:22:41Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_002", "eventType": "sentence_modified", "claimId": "clm_luke_001", "fromRevisionId": 1280001003, "toRevisionId": 1280001004, "section": "Biography", "before": "Luke Skywalker was the son of Anakin Skywalker, a Jedi Knight who served as a general during the Clone Wars before falling to the dark side and becoming the Sith Lord Darth Vader.", "after": "Luke Skywalker was the son of Anakin Skywalker, a former slave from Tatooine discovered by Jedi Master Qui-Gon Jinn, who believed Anakin to be the Chosen One of Jedi prophecy. Anakin became a Jedi Knight and Clone Wars hero before falling to the dark side, becoming the Sith Lord Darth Vader under the influence of Emperor Palpatine.", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "The claim was expanded from 1 sentence to 3 sentences with the addition of Anakin's origin (former slave from Tatooine) and the Chosen One prophecy.", "detail": "Expanded after the 1999-2005 prequel trilogy provided detailed backstory. The Qui-Gon Jinn and Chosen One elements were added."}, {"fact": "The phrase 'under the influence of Emperor Palpatine' was added to contextualize Anakin's fall.", "detail": "This reflects the narrative introduced in Revenge of the Sith (2005) showing Palpatine's deliberate manipulation."}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2023-08-10T14:55:20Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_003", "eventType": "section_reorganized", "claimId": null, "fromRevisionId": 1280001005, "toRevisionId": 1280001006, "section": "Powers and Abilities", "before": "(Section contained a chronological list of Force abilities demonstrated across the films)", "after": "(Section reorganized into three eras: 'Original Trilogy Era', 'Post-Return of the Jedi (Legends)', and 'Sequel Trilogy Era')", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "The section was split into three era-specific subsections to resolve disputes about which abilities were canon.", "detail": "Reorganization followed a talk page discussion where editors could not agree on whether Legends-era Force abilities (e.g., projecting a Force illusion across the galaxy) should be listed alongside film-depicted abilities."}, {"fact": "The 'Post-Return of the Jedi (Legends)' subsection was marked with a {{Legends}} banner.", "detail": "This followed Wookieepedia's 2014 policy change mandating clear separation of Canon and Legends content."}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2023-09-25T11:10:33Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_004", "eventType": "talk_thread_opened", "claimId": null, "fromRevisionId": 1280001007, "toRevisionId": 1280001008, "section": "Talk:Luke Skywalker", "before": "", "after": "The 'Sequel Trilogy Era' subsection currently describes Luke as having 'cut himself off from the Force.' Multiple editors have noted this is an oversimplification of The Last Jedi. Luke's arc in TLJ shows him reconnecting with the Force, not permanently severing his connection. I propose: 'Luke chose to exile himself and suppress his connection to the Force following his failure with Ben Solo, though he reconnected with it during the events leading to the Battle of Crait.'", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "A new talk page thread titled 'Luke's Force connection in sequel era \u2014 cut off or suppressed?' was opened.", "detail": "Started by user ForceLoreAnalyst on 2023-11-12T19:33:45Z."}, {"fact": "The thread argues that 'cut off' implies permanence that contradicts Luke's actions in the third act of The Last Jedi.", "detail": "The editor proposed replacing 'cut off' with 'chosen exile and suppressed his connection,' citing on-screen evidence of Force reconnection."}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2023-11-12T19:33:45Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_005", "eventType": "sentence_modified", "claimId": "clm_luke_002", "fromRevisionId": 1280001009, "toRevisionId": 1280001010, "section": "Powers and Abilities", "before": "Luke Skywalker was the most powerful Jedi in galactic history, surpassing even Yoda and his father Anakin in raw Force potential.", "after": "Luke Skywalker was among the most powerful Jedi of his era. His midi-chlorian count, while never officially stated in canon, was implied through lineage to be comparable to his father Anakin's pre-injury count. His demonstrated feats\u2014including the projection of a convincing Force illusion across interstellar distances\u2014indicate a level of mastery rarely achieved.", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "The superlative 'most powerful Jedi in galactic history' was removed.", "detail": "Editor noted that the 2017 reference book 'Star Wars: The Last Jedi: The Visual Dictionary' describes Luke as 'the most powerful Jedi of his era' but does not make a trans-historical claim."}, {"fact": "Qualitative language ('among the most powerful') and evidentiary framing ('his demonstrated feats...indicate') replaced the absolute claim.", "detail": "This follows Wookieepedia's sourcing policy that superlatives must be directly attributable to canonical sources."}, {"fact": "The Force-projection-on-Crait feat was added as the primary evidence for Luke's power level.", "detail": "This feat is unique in Star Wars canon and provides a concrete, on-screen metric for Luke's abilities without requiring the contested 'most powerful' framing."}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2023-12-08T16:40:55Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_006", "eventType": "citation_replaced", "claimId": "clm_luke_003", "fromRevisionId": 1280001011, "toRevisionId": 1280001012, "section": "Relationship with Darth Vader", "before": "Luke's belief that there was still good in Vader ultimately proved correct when Vader sacrificed himself to save Luke from the Emperor during the Battle of Endor. [22]", "after": "Luke's belief that there was still good in Vader ultimately proved correct when Vader sacrificed himself to save Luke from the Emperor during the Battle of Endor. The 2015 novel 'Return of the Jedi: Beware the Power of the Dark Side!' provides Vader's internal monologue during the throne room confrontation, confirming that Anakin Skywalker's consciousness resurfaced when he saw his son being tortured. [22][47]", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "New citation [47] was added: Angleberger, T. (2015). 'Return of the Jedi: Beware the Power of the Dark Side!' Disney-Lucasfilm Press.", "detail": "This novelization includes Vader's first-person perspective on the throne room scene, providing canonical confirmation of Anakin's mental state during his redemption."}, {"fact": "The claim was expanded to include Vader's internal monologue as corroborating evidence.", "detail": "This addresses a long-standing fan debate about whether Vader's sacrifice was motivated by paternal love or Sith self-interest."}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2024-01-20T10:15:30Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_007", "eventType": "revert_detected", "claimId": "clm_luke_004", "fromRevisionId": 1280001013, "toRevisionId": 1280001014, "section": "Biography", "before": "After Ben Solo's fall to the dark side and the destruction of Luke's new Jedi temple, Luke went into self-imposed exile on Ahch-To, blaming himself for the failure.", "after": "After Ben Solo's fall to the dark side and the destruction of Luke's new Jedi temple, Luke went into self-imposed exile on Ahch-To, blaming himself for the failure.", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "Revision 1280001013 was an exact revert of revision 1280001012.", "detail": "An anonymous editor had appended '\u2014a cowardly act that contributed to the deaths of billions in the Hosnian Cataclysm' to the exile description. Reverted by moderator RebelAllianceArchivist with summary: 'rv \u2014 adding editorial moral judgment in wiki voice. Use talk page to discuss framing.'"}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2024-03-05T08:45:12Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_008", "eventType": "sentence_modified", "claimId": "clm_luke_005", "fromRevisionId": 1280001015, "toRevisionId": 1280001016, "section": "Legacy", "before": "Luke's new Jedi Order, as depicted in Legends continuity, trained several notable Jedi including his niece Jaina Solo and nephew Jacen Solo.", "after": "Luke's new Jedi Order in Legends continuity trained a generation of Jedi Knights at the Jedi Praxeum on Yavin 4, including his niece Jaina Solo Fel (eventually the Sword of the Jedi), his nephew Jacen Solo (who fell to the dark side as Darth Caedus), his son Ben Skywalker, and Jedi from multiple species including Bothans, Twi'leks, and Ithorians. The Praxeum admitted its first class in 11 ABY and operated for over three decades before the Yuuzhan Vong invasion and subsequent reconstruction.", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "The claim was expanded from a sentence fragment to a full paragraph with institutional and temporal detail.", "detail": "Added the Praxeum's founding year (11 ABY), multi-species composition, and 30+ year operational timeline."}, {"fact": "The fates of Jaina Solo Fel and Jacen Solo/Darth Caedus were made explicit rather than left to reader inference.", "detail": "The editor cited Star Wars: The New Jedi Order series and Star Wars: Legacy of the Force series as sources."}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2024-04-18T13:22:40Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_009", "eventType": "sentence_modified", "claimId": "clm_luke_006", "fromRevisionId": 1280001017, "toRevisionId": 1280001018, "section": "Biography", "before": "In the sequel trilogy, Luke Skywalker had become disillusioned with the Jedi Order's legacy and believed the galaxy would be better off without the Jedi.", "after": "In the sequel trilogy, Luke Skywalker had become disillusioned with the Jedi Order's historical failures\u2014citing the Order's arrogance during the Clone Wars, its role in enabling Palpatine's rise, and its failure to prevent Anakin's fall. His belief that the Jedi should end was presented as a period of crisis, not a permanent conviction, as evidenced by his ultimate declaration that 'I will not be the last Jedi' before confronting his former student Kylo Ren.", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "The claim was expanded to include Luke's specific grievances (Jedi arrogance, Palpatine enablement, Anakin's fall).", "detail": "Editor cited direct dialogue from The Last Jedi where Luke enumerates Jedi failures to Rey."}, {"fact": "A temporal framing ('period of crisis, not permanent conviction') was added along with Luke's final words in the film.", "detail": "This addresses the talk page consensus that the previous framing misrepresented Luke's arc as static rather than a crisis resolved by the film's end."}], "layer": "model_interpretation", "timestamp": "2024-06-30T15:10:18Z"}
{"eventId": "evt_luke_010", "eventType": "talk_thread_archived", "claimId": null, "fromRevisionId": 1280001019, "toRevisionId": 1280001020, "section": "Talk:Luke Skywalker", "before": "(Active thread: 'Luke's Force connection in sequel era \u2014 cut off or suppressed?' with 18 replies over 7 months)", "after": "(Thread closed by community consensus after the article text was changed to 'suppressed his connection' with a footnote noting the interpretive dispute and directing readers to the talk page archive)", "deterministicFacts": [{"fact": "The Luke Force-connection thread was archived after reaching consensus on the wording change.", "detail": "The closing editor was user ForceModerator, who noted that 13 of 18 replies supported 'suppressed' as the more accurate term."}, {"fact": "A compromise footnote was added to the article acknowledging that some sources describe the action as 'cutting off' while the article uses 'suppressed' based on in-universe consistency.", "detail": "This represents a form of interpretive dispute resolution where the community acknowledges ambiguity while adopting a specific editorial stance."}], "layer": "observed", "timestamp": "2024-08-22T11:05:00Z"}
